          "body": "The third oracle (vv.13-19) is the most geographically detailed section in the Egypt-oracle cycle, naming nine cities or regions in a systematic sweep from the Delta to the deep south. The judgment on Memphis is distinctive: God will 'destroy the idols and make the images cease' (v.13). The Hebrew words are *gillulim* (dung-pellets — Ezekiel's derogatory term for idols) and *elilim* (worthless things — Isaiah's word). Memphis was home to the Apis bull cult, one of Egypt's most prestigious animal-deity systems. God does not merely defeat Egypt militarily; He humiliates her gods in their own cult center. The absence of a prince (v.13) completes the picture: no gods, no king — a nation emptied of every source of identity and authority. The spreading fire through Zoan, Thebes, Pelusium, On, Pi-beseth, and Tehaphnehes follows the logic of total and irreversible judgment. When 'the day will be dark' in Tehaphnehes (v.18) — the border fortress through which Egypt projected power into Canaan — the darkness is not meteorological but theological: the cloud that once marked God's presence with Israel now marks His judgment on Egypt."
